frameDefinitions: An Agent acts to  cause a Experiencer to feel a certain emotion.
The words in this frame describe situations in which an Agent or a Cause injures a Victim.
An Experiencer is involved in a bodily injury to a Body_part.
These are words relating to filling containers and covering areas with some thing, things or substance, the Theme.
An Agent or Cause affects a Body_part of an Experiencer so that the quality of the Experiencer's perceptual experience of the Body_part is qualitatively changed.
An Entity undergoes some change (the Event) that is (or is construed as) punctual.
frameExamples: I was so <t>offended</t> by her behaviour towards me.
Rod saw his father <t>beating</t> his mother.
I think that I <t>hurt</t> myself pretty bad back there.
Lionel Hutz <t>coated</t> the wall with paint.
Chandra <t>massaged</t> Liliana's wrist because it was injured.
This <t>happens</t> to me all the time.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Agent</fen> is the person who's action's cause an emotion in the <fen>Experiencer</fen>.
The Experiencer feels an emotion as caused by the <fen>Agent</fen>.
The <fen>Event</fen> is the occasion or happening that evokes emotions in the <fen>Experiencer</fen>. This <fen>Event</fen> occurs as the direct result of a sentient being's actions.
When the Agent causes emotion in the Experiencer.
The location where the <fen>Agent</fen> causes the <fen>Experiencer</fen> to feel the emotion.
<fen>Agent</fen> is the person causing the <fen>Victim</fen>'s injury.

The <fen>Victim</fen> is the being or entity that is injured.  If the <fen>Victim</fen> is included in the phrase indicating <fen>Body_part</fen>, the <fen>Victim</fen> role is tagged on a second role layer (see 3rd example).
The <fen>Body_part</fen> identifies the location on the body where the bodily injury takes place.
The <fen>Cause</fen> marks expressions that indicate some non-intentional, typically non-human, force that inflicts harm on the <fen>Victim</fen>
<fen>Time</fen> identifies the time when the harm-causing event occurs.
<fen>Place</fen> identifies the place where the harm causing event occurs.
The location on the body of the <fen>Experiencer</fen> where the bodily injury takes place.
The being or entity that is injured.
The time when the harming event occurs.
The place where the harming event occurs.
The <fen>Agent</fen> is the actor who instigates the filling.
The <fen>Theme</fen> is the physical object or substance which changes location.
The <fen>Goal</fen> is the area or container being filled. Goal is generally the NP Object in this frame.
An event which brings about the filling of the <fen>Goal</fen>.
When the filling occurs.
Where the filling takes place.
The <fen>Agent</fen> is the person causing a bodily experience in the <fen>Experiencer</fen>.
The <fen>Experiencer</fen> is the being or entity whose experience changes.
>The <fen>Body_part</fen> identifies the location on the <fen>Experiencer</fen>'s body where the bodily experience takes place.
The <fen>Cause</fen> marks expressions that indicate some non-intentional, typically non-human, force that affects the <fen>Experiencer</fen>'s <fen>Body_part</fen>.
<fen>Time</fen> identifies the time when the experience-causing event occurs.
<fen>Place</fen> identifies the place where the bodily experience is caused.
This role identifies the event which occurs and affects the <fen>Entity</fen>.
This role identifies the entity, concrete or abstract.
This role identifies the time when the event occurs.
This role identifies where the event takes place.
